            <div
              class="prose dark:prose-invert text-base-700 dark:text-base-300 max-w-none leading-relaxed"
            >
              <p>
                Guido X Jansen is a Community Builder with {yearsBuilding}+
                years creating technical ecosystems. Founded Dutchento/Meet
                Magento, created CRO.CAFE podcast, and led Spryker's enterprise
                community. Cognitive psychologist turned DevRel leader. {
                  talksCount
                } talks across {countryCount} countries. Open source and privacy advocate.
                Based in the Netherlands.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class={card}>
            <h3 class="font-display mb-4 text-[1.1rem] font-bold">
              Medium Bio (100 words)
            </h3>
            <div
              class="prose dark:prose-invert text-base-700 dark:text-base-300 max-w-none space-y-4 leading-relaxed"
            >
              <p>
                Guido X Jansen is a Community Builder who creates technical
                ecosystems that drive business growth. He has built community
                functions from zero multiple times: Dutchento/Meet Magento (600+
                annual attendees), CRO.CAFE (200+ podcast episodes), and
                Spryker's enterprise community (130+ clients).
              </p>
              <p>
                His cognitive psychology background taught him you can't
                reliably predict how technical users will behave, so he designs
                community work as experiments and measures what creates real
                business value instead of chasing activity metrics. He has
                spoken at {talksCount} talks across {countryCount} countries.
              </p>
              <p>
                Guido advocates for open source, privacy-first technology, and
                building resilient systems. Based in the Netherlands, working
                remotely.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class={card}>
            <h3 class="font-display mb-4 text-[1.1rem] font-bold">
              Long Bio (200 words)
            </h3>
            <div
              class="prose dark:prose-invert text-base-700 dark:text-base-300 max-w-none space-y-4 leading-relaxed"
            >
              <p>
                Guido X Jansen is a Community Builder who turns technical
                ecosystems into real business growth. With {yearsBuilding}+
                years at the intersection of psychology and technology, he has
                built community functions from zero multiple times: in the early
                2000s with Mambo/Joomla!, as founder of Dutchento/Meet Magento
                (scaling to 600+ annual attendees), as creator of CRO.CAFE (200+
                episodes across four languages), and at Spryker (serving 130+
                enterprise clients).
              </p>
              <p>
                His cognitive psychology background shapes how he approaches
                every community decision. Rather than assuming he knows why
                developers and technical users behave the way they do, he treats
                it as something to test: building onboarding that turns
                newcomers into contributors, feedback mechanisms that surface
                real sentiment, and a working sense of the difference between
                activity and engagement.
              </p>
              <p>
                Guido operates at the intersection of community, product, and
                customer success. At Spryker, community-driven initiatives
                influenced 25% of product roadmap decisions. He has presented at
                {talksCount} talks across {countryCount} countries on topics including
                composable commerce, community building, and digital psychology. He
                advocates for open source principles, privacy protection, and building
                systems that get stronger under pressure instead of barely surviving
                it.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

